{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538308","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538308"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:26:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16157"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16157"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.11,0.3,0.08,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8848"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101463"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8848","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8848"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16157"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83902"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1432"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"2583"},{"type":"tags","id":"3688"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4669"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21089"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35087"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101463","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101463"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-week history of painful swelling in his left groin. He reports having unprotected receptive anal intercourse six weeks ago. He also describes fatigue, fever, and muscle aches for the past week. He has had alternating constipation and diarrhoea  during this time, with tenesmus and anal pain.  He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There is tender unilateral left inguinal lymphadenopathy with overlying erythema. Rectal swabs and ulcer swabs were performed. No genital ulcers are present. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Excision biopsy of lymph node for histology","Herpes simplex virus polymerase chain reaction","Treponema pallidum antibody test","Gram stain of lymph node aspirate","Lymph node aspirate for nucleic acid amplification testing"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of Lymphogranuloma venereum (LGV), caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E serovars L1, L2, or L3. The presentation includes painful inguinal lymphadenopathy, constitutional symptoms, and symptoms of proctitis or a painful genital ulcer. The diagnosis needs to be confirmed with appropriate testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymph node aspirate for nucleic acid amplification testing\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard diagnostic test for LGV. This test can detect \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E DNA and subsequent molecular typing can identify the L serovars group of Chlamydia responsible for LGV. In patients with proctitis or a genital ulcer without lymph node involvement, a swab sent for Chlamydia NAAT would be appropriate alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus polymerase chain reaction\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were visible genital or anal ulcers, which are not present in this case. While herpes can cause lymphadenopathy, it typically presents with painful vesicular lesions and the symptoms would typically resolve within two weeks. Furthermore, viral prodromal symptoms of fatigue and fever usually begin prior to or at the same time the rash occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETreponema pallidum antibody testing\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose syphilis. While syphilis can cause lymphadenopathy, it is typically painless and bilateral. The acute presentation with constitutional symptoms is more consistent with LGV.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcision biopsy of lymph node\u003C/strong\u003E is overly invasive as a first-line investigation and should be reserved for cases where malignancy is suspected or when less invasive tests are inconclusive.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram stain\u003C/strong\u003E of lymph node aspirate would not be helpful as \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E is an intracellular organism that cannot be visualised with Gram staining. This test would only be useful if a secondary bacterial infection was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lymphogranuloma venereum classically presents with painful inguinal lymphadenopathy and constitutional symptoms.","Nucleic acid amplification testing of lymph node aspirate is the gold standard for diagnosis of lymphogranuloma venereum with lymph node involvement."],"references":["Ceovic R, Jerkovic Gulin S. Lymphogranuloma venereum: diagnostic and treatment challenges. Infection and Drug Resistance [Internet]. 2015 Mar;39. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4381887/","Lymphogranuloma venereum - STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. STI Guidelines Australia. 2021. Available at: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/lymphogranuloma-venereum/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83902"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16157"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83902","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83902"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-02T00:59:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-02T01:00:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8848"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101463"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"37","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/37"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf46","name":"Sexual Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,